By Pearl’s axioms (Pearl, 2009), adding an edge does not "extend" a DAG; it annihilates it, replacing it with a novel graph $G'$. A new edge fundamentally alters the Markov equivalence class, opening previously blocked back-door paths and destroying the d-separation structure upon which any graphical theorem or structural equation relies. You cannot logically claim $G$ is fixed in advance while simultaneously permitting dynamic edge instantiation. If the graph mutates, the structural equations $F$ originally governing $G$ are invalidated. (Furthermore, this exposes a glaring formal contradiction in your developmental scaling: your system dictates that humans asymptote at State 8.999..., yet requires humans to enter State 10 to trigger this Royal Purple edge-creation).

